Here's a C++ function that takes a std::string containing markdown text and returns a std::string containing HTML-formatted text:

```cpp
// Take a markdown string and return an HTML string
std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdownString) {
    // Split the markdown string into lines using the '\n' character
    std::vector<std::string> lines = splitString(markdownString, '\n');

    // Initialize an HTML string to return
    std::string htmlString;

    // Loop through each line of the markdown string
    for (const auto& line : lines) {
        // Replace all instances of the markdown syntax with HTML equivalents
        line = replaceMarkdownToHtml(line);
        // Add the line to the HTML string
        htmlString += line;
    }

    // Return the HTML string
    return htmlString;
}
```
`splitString()` is an internal function that takes a single string as input and returns a `std::vector` containing all of the lines of text in that string. This is useful for splitting the input into lines of text. `replaceMarkdownToHtml()` is another internal function that takes a single line of text as input and returns a modified version of that line. This function replaces any instances of the Markdown syntax with their equivalent HTML syntax, making the output more readable in HTML format.

